  "prompt": "Now that India has banned 500 & 1000 notes, what will people with excess of such notes accrued as black money do? Can they still escape?",
  "response": "When India demonetized 500 and 1000 rupee notes in November 2016, people with large amounts of unaccounted black money had limited options:\n\n1. Deposit options:\n- Could deposit money in banks with identification\n- Deposits above certain limits attracted tax and penalties\n- Substantial unexplained deposits triggered tax investigations\n\n2. Conversion challenges:\n- Limited window for exchanging old notes\n- Strict documentation requirements\n- High scrutiny of large deposits\n\n3. Consequences for black money holders:\n- Pay taxes and penalties\n- Risk income tax investigations\n- Potential legal consequences for tax evasion\n- Some money became effectively worthless\n\n4. Limited escape routes:\n- Buying gold\n- Converting to other assets quickly\n- Transferring to family/associates\n- Using hawala transactions\n\n5. Government measures:\n- Implemented stricter KYC norms\n- Enhanced digital transaction tracking\n- Increased tax surveillance\n- Introduced Goods and Services Tax (GST)\n\nThe demonetization significantly disrupted black money circulation, forcing many to either declare income or lose substantial unaccounted wealth. While some might have found ways to circumvent the system, the overall impact was considerable in reducing undeclared cash in the economy.",
